- Dislikes: multi‑artist or regionally eclectic anthologies, incomplete/“Vol. 1” fragments, excessively bright/overproduced radio mixes, and early‑60s raw single‑focused sets that trade warmth for grit.
Evaluation and rationale
- How The Very Best of Chicago: Only the Beginning maps to my preferences:
  - It is a single‑artist anthology/greatest‑hits collection, which directly matches my stated top preference for single‑artist, complete greatest‑hits sets.
  - The description emphasises AOR/soft‑rock qualities with polished yet natural production, which aligns with my liking for a late‑70s/AOR sheen and mixes that preserve dynamics.
  - It calls out tight multi‑part vocal harmonies and signature horns/guitars — that satisfies my desire for crystal harmonies and tasteful horn arrangements as part of a fuller band sound.
  - Varied dynamics and consistent mastering avoid the hyper‑compressed radio sound I dislike.
  - The anthology is “expertly sequenced to read like a unified album,” matching my value on cohesive sequencing, collector‑appeal, and mood‑creating track order.
  - The format (concise, recognisable hits gathered into a single‑artist package) suits my preference for tracks that encourage repeated listening and communal singing.
- How Moondance maps to my preferences (and where it falls short relative to Chicago):
  - Moondance is very strong on warm, analog production, mid‑tempo/melody‑first songwriting, lush vocal warmth, tasteful horns/piano, acoustic textures, and dynamics‑preserving mixes — all qualities I explicitly value.
  - It also rewards full‑album repeat listening and offers studio restraint and intentional sequencing, which I appreciate.
  - However, Moondance is a single studio album rather than a greatest‑hits anthology. My first stated preference is for single‑artist, complete greatest‑hits collections that deliver concise, recognisable tracks assembled for repeat/communal listening and collector appeal. While Moondance is cohesive and sonically excellent, it does not fulfill the “complete greatest‑hits collection” brief and therefore misses a top priority.
  - Additionally, although Moondance offers lush intimacy, the Chicago set’s emphasis on hook‑forward AOR anthems and multi‑part vocal arrangements more directly serves my preference for singalong, communal tracks — the Chicago compilation collects many such moments in one place, whereas Moondance is one cohesive statement rather than a catalogue of recognisable singalong hits.
Decision summary
- I choose The Very Best of Chicago: Only the Beginning because it aligns with my highest‑priority preferences: a single‑artist greatest‑hits anthology that preserves natural dynamics, features tight multi‑part vocal harmonies and tasteful horns/guitars, and is expertly sequenced to function like a unified, collector‑friendly album of concise, recognisable, singalong tracks. Moondance is sonically very appealing and matches many production and sequencing preferences, but it is a single studio album rather than the complete greatest‑hits, hook‑forward compilation I said I prefer, so it is the less fitting choice given my stated priorities.

