rmony and restraint: The remaster notes “tight, hook‑serving harmonies,” which fits my “harmony‑first” taste and my preference for tightly integrated ensemble vocals rather than a single vocal pinned in front. Early Beatles arrangements tend to use harmonies and modest overdubs as texture, which matches my tolerance for inventive but restrained multitracking.\n- Analog warmth with preserved dynamics: The remaster is described as having “lived‑in analog warmth preserving punch and clarity” and “punchy transients with tasteful hiss reduction.” That aligns with my value on remasters that preserve transient punch and micro‑dynamics (and my dislike of hyper‑compression/brick‑wall mastering). The mention of lively room ambience also supports the dynamic, breathing mixes I prefer.\n- Instrument separation and vintage color: “Clear instrument separation” plus room ambience and tasteful hiss reduction suggest mixes that let arrangements breathe and reveal vintage/acoustic color (recessed guitars, tasteful keys) — another stated preference.\nWhy I reject the single‑artist Greatest Hits (the alternate candidate):\n- Compilation provenance vs. authentic album flow: Even though it’s “sequenced to play front‑to‑back like an album,” a Greatest Hits package is still a compilation of tracks from different sessions/eras. My preference strongly favors an original single‑artist LP that was conceived as a contiguous listening experience; a greatest‑hits compilation—even well sequenced—tends to lack the cohesive storytelling and consistent production character I prize.\n- Vocal‑forward emphasis risks violating a key dislike: The Greatest Hits is described as “theatrical yet intimate lead vocals” and “suits listeners who prefer vocal‑forward mixes.” I explicitly dislike lead‑forward mastering that pins a solo vocal ahead of the band. While I do accept intimate theatrical leads in appropriate contexts, the phrasing suggests a consistently lead‑forward presentation and heavily polished mult