The user updates his self-description as follows: I now favor polished classic R&B/funk singles with a warm, cohesive studio sheen: concise 3–4‑minute, melody‑first tracks that are groove‑ and bass‑forward with tight low end, punchy drums, and horn punches that propel the beat without burying vocals. I prefer cohesive, consistently matched mastering with modest, musical compression for steady perceived loudness (not brick‑wall), preserving transient snap and punch while keeping tracks danceable and radio‑ready. Front‑center lead vocals with tasteful studio polish and stacked harmonies are essential, as are sequencing that sustains momentum and bass‑driven arrangements that invite movement. From my earlier tastes I retain a love of polished multitracked harmonies, clear instrument separation that supports groove rather than exposes microdetail, tasteful keys/strings for vintage color, and mastering that keeps warmth without flattening presence. Dislikes: hyper‑compressed/brick‑wall limiting; airy, detail‑forward/headroom‑first mastering or slap‑back ambience that thins bass; roomy mixes that bury the lead; meandering sequencing and choppy multi‑artist compilations.

